article.description:
Chelsea Trotter scored 16 points to lead a
balanced attack and No. 5 Stanford beat Boston University 69-55 on
Saturday.
article.headline: Cardinal finding identity without All-American Powell
article.linkText: Balance works in Stanford's win over Boston University
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- With its go-to player out of the lineup, Stanford
is finding that the key to staying among the nation's elite is
balance.

	   Chelsea Trotter scored a career-high 16 points to lead five
players in double figures as No. 5 Stanford beat Boston University
69-55 on Saturday.

	   Stanford (6-1) controlled the game from the opening minutes and
bounced back from its first loss, a 71-56 setback at No. 4
Tennessee on Wednesday.

	   "I can't tell you that I thought we played especially well, but
this team has basically found a way to win with the exception of
one game," Stanford coach Tara VanDerveer said. "I just think we
got aggressive and made some shots down the stretch and that was
the difference."

	   The Cardinal had a major setback when Pac-10 Player of the Year
and preseason first-team All-American Nicole Powell was sidelined
with a bulging disk in her lower back.

	   Powell hasn't played all year, and is still out indefinitely,
but Stanford has rolled by getting key performances from different
players each time out. Five different players have been the high
scorer for the Cardinal, a team without a senior.

	   "This team is finding its identity. It's a really young group,
and have had some severe injury problems," VanDerveer said. "I
give this team a lot of credit."

	   Stanford broke open the game midway through the second half. The
Terriers cut Stanford's lead to 45-36 with 11:48 left, but Stanford
responded with a 16-3 run highlighted by 3-pointers from Kelley
Suminski and Sebnem Kimyacioglu.

	   Suminski punctuated the Cardinal burst with a steal and layup
that pushed the lead to 59-39.

	   The Cardinal defense forced BU into poor shots and held the
Terriers to 33 percent shooting. BU went more than five minutes
without a field goal late in the first half as Stanford
methodically extended its lead from 22-16 to 33-19.

	   "Their poison was inside in the first half," BU coach Margaret
McKeon said. "In the second half they were able to hit some
3-point shots."

	   Stanford outrebounded the Terriers 24-13 in the first half,
46-30 in the game. But BU stayed close by forcing Stanford into 11
first-half turnovers. BU's Katie Terhune led all scorers in the
half with 10 points.

	   The Terriers outscored the Cardinal 7-2 in the final 1:35 of the
half to cut Stanford's lead to 35-26 at halftime.

	   Terhune scored 19 points to lead BU, and Marisa Moseley added 11
points. Suminski scored 12 points for Stanford, and T'Nae Thiel
added 10 points and a career-high 15 rebounds.

	   Stanford was BU's highest-ranked opponent since February 1982,
when the Terriers lost to No. 3 Old Dominion 90-63. It was also the
first meeting between the teams.
